text: Zeus is The king of the gods, the ruler of Mount Olympus, and the god of the sky, lightning, thunder, law, order, and justice. Symbols: Thunderbolt, Eagle, Oak
Athena is Goddess of wisdom, war, and crafts. Patroness of Athens. Symbols: Owl, Aegis (shield)
Hestia is Goddess of the hearth, home, and domesticity. Symbols: Hearth, Fire
Apollo is God of music, poetry, prophecy, and medicine. Twin brother of Artemis. Symbols: Lyre, Sun chariot
Artemis is Goddess of the hunt, wilderness, and childbirth. Twin sister of Apollo. Symbols: Bow and arrows, Deer
Poseidon is God of the sea, earthquakes, and horses. Brother of Zeus and Hades. Symbols: Trident, Horse
Hades is God of the underworld and the dead. Brother of Zeus and Poseidon. Symbols: Bident, Helmet of invisibility
Demeter is Goddess of agriculture, fertility, and the harvest. Sister of Zeus, Poseidon, Hades, and Hestia. Symbols: Wheat, Cornucopia
Aphrodite is Goddess of love, beauty, and desire. Born from the sea foam. Symbols: Dove, Rose
Hera is Goddess of marriage, women, and childbirth. Queen of the gods, sister and wife of Zeus. Symbols: Peacock, Cow
Dionysus is God of wine, parties, and festivals. Patron of the arts. Symbols: Wine cup (kantharos), Grapevine
Ares is God of war, violence, and bloodshed. Son of Zeus and Hera. Symbols: Spear, Helmet
Hephaestus is God of fire, metalworking, and craftsmanship. Son of Zeus and Hera. Symbols: Hammer, Anvil
Hercules (Heracles) is A divine hero and the greatest of the Greek warriors, known for his strength and numerous adventures. Symbols: Club, Lion skin
Persephone is Goddess of springtime and queen of the underworld. Daughter of Demeter. Symbols: Pomegranate, Spring flowers
Hermes is God of trade, thieves, travelers, sports, and border crossings. Messenger of the gods. Symbols: Caduceus, Winged sandals
Pan is God of the wild, shepherds, flocks, and rustic music. Symbols: Goat, Pan flute
Nyx is Goddess of the night and mother of many deities. Symbols: Stars, Night sky
Eros (Cupid) is God of love, attraction, and affection. Son of Aphrodite. Symbols: Bow and arrows, Hearts
Nemesis is Goddess of retribution, vengeance, and divine justice. Symbols: Wheel, Sword
Aeolus is God of the winds. Symbols: Wind, Jar
Boreas is God of the north wind and winter. Symbols: North wind, Cold
Zephyrus is God of the west wind. Symbols: West wind, Gentle breeze
Eurus is God of the east wind. Symbols: East wind, Storms
Notus is God of the south wind. Symbols: South wind, Hot wind
Anemoi is Collective term for the gods of the winds. Symbols: Winds
Eos is Goddess of the dawn who opens the gates of heaven for the sun each day. Symbols: Dew, Rosy fingers
Iris is Goddess of the rainbow and messenger of the gods. Symbols: Rainbow, Caduceus
Tyche is Goddess of fortune and prosperity. Symbols: Cornucopia, Wheel
Nike is Goddess of victory. Daughter of Pallas and Styx. Symbols: Wings, Laurel wreath
Hebe is Goddess of youth and cupbearer to the gods. Symbols: Cup, Eagle
Asclepius is God of medicine and healing. Symbols: Serpent-entwined staff
Hypnos is God of sleep. Symbols: Poppy, River Lethe
Erebus is God of darkness and shadow. Brother and consort of Nyx. Symbols: Shadow, Darkness
Gaia is Primordial goddess of the earth. Mother of the Titans and many other beings. Symbols: Earth, Trees
Uranus is Primordial god of the sky. Father of the Titans. Symbols: Sky, Stars
Thanatos is God of death. Symbols: Butterfly, Sword
Hecate is Goddess of magic, witchcraft, and ghosts. Symbols: Torch, Keys
Janus is Roman god of beginnings, gates, transitions, time, duality, doorways, passages, and endings. Symbols: Two-faced head, Doors
Morpheus is God of dreams. Symbols: Wings, Poppy
Cronus is Titan ruler of the universe until overthrown by his son, Zeus. Symbols: Sickle, Hourglass
Atlas is Titan condemned to hold up the sky for eternity. Symbols: Globe, Celestial sphere
Hecate is Goddess of magic, witchcraft, and crossroads. Symbols: Torch, Dagger
Oceanus is Titan god of the ocean and rivers that encircle the world. Symbols: River, Ocean waves
Prometheus is Titan who stole fire from Mount Olympus and gave it to humanity. Creator of mankind. Symbols: Fire, Torch
Hyperion is Titan of heavenly light, associated with the sun. Symbols: Sun, Golden chariot
Theia is Titaness associated with sight and heavenly light. Symbols: Shining halo, Ethereal veil
Crius is Titan of constellations and heavenly constellations. Symbols: Star map, Celestial globe
Mnemosyne is Titaness of memory and mother of the Muses. Symbols: Memory scroll, Memory pool
Phoebe is Titaness associated with prophecy and the moon. Symbols: Oracle staff, Moon phases
Coeus is Titan of intellect and questioning. Symbols: Scales, Book of knowledge
Themis is Titaness of divine law, order, and justice. Symbols: Scales of justice, Law book
Tethys is Titaness of fresh water and motherhood. Symbols: Spring, Nurturing bowl
Thea is Titaness associated with sight and divine radiance. Symbols: Bright halo, Shimmering aura
Rhea is Titaness associated with fertility and motherhood. Symbols: Cornucopia, Fertile soil
Iapetus is Titan associated with mortality and human life-span. Symbols: Chain, Human figurine
Clymene is Titaness associated with fame and renown. Symbols: Laurel wreath, Celebratory torch
Epimetheus is Titan associated with afterthought and hindsight. Symbols: Closed box, Broken chains
Menoetius is Titan associated with rash action and reckless anger. Symbols: Lightning bolt, Tempest
Perses is Titan associated with destruction and war. Symbols: Flaming sword, War helmet
Pallas is Titan associated with war strategy and foresight. Symbols: Strategist's map, Battle flag
Astraeus is Titan associated with stars and nocturnal prophecy. Symbols: Stellar globe, Nocturnal veil
Eos is Titaness associated with dawn and rosy-fingered morning. Symbols: Rosy veil, Morning dew
Lelantos is Titan associated with air and the hunter's skill of stalking prey. Symbols: Bow and arrow, Hunting cloak
Metis is Titaness of wisdom, prudence, and deep thought. Symbols: Owl, Wisdom scroll
Styx is Titaness of the river Styx and personification of hatred. Symbols: Black river, Adamantine gates
Helios is Titan god of the sun. Symbols: Chariot, Solar disc
Selene is Titaness of the moon. Symbols: Crescent moon, Torch
Orpheus is Legendary musician, poet, and prophet in the Greek myths. Son of Apollo. Symbols: Lyre, Orphic tablets
Theseus is Hero and king of Athens, slayer of the Minotaur. Symbols: Sword, Thread
Achilles is Greek hero of the Trojan War, known for his strength and bravery. Symbols: Shield, Spear
Perseus is Slayer of Medusa and rescuer of Andromeda. Symbols: Gorgon's head, Winged sandals
Aeneas is Trojan hero, the son of Aphrodite and Anchises. Symbols: Golden bough, Shield
Jason is Leader of the Argonauts in the quest for the Golden Fleece. Symbols: Golden Fleece, Argo
Bellerophon is Hero who tamed the winged horse Pegasus and defeated the Chimera. Symbols: Pegasus, Bridle
Castor is One of the Dioscuri, twin brother of Pollux, known for his skill in horsemanship. Symbols: Horse, Spear
Pollux is One of the Dioscuri, twin brother of Castor, known for his boxing skills. Symbols: Boxing gloves, Horse
Ganymede is Beautiful Trojan prince abducted by Zeus to be the cup-bearer to the gods. Symbols: Cup, Eagle
Hippolytus is Son of Theseus, known for his chastity and tragic death. Symbols: Chariot, Horses
Meleager is Hero of the Calydonian Boar Hunt. Symbols: Spear, Boar
Phaethon is Son of Helios, known for his tragic attempt to drive the sun chariot. Symbols: Sun chariot, Horses
Atalanta is Famous huntress and runner, known for her role in the Calydonian Boar Hunt. Symbols: Bow and arrows, Hunting dogs
Orpheus is Musician and poet who could charm anyone with his music. Symbols: Lyre, Laurel wreath
Theseus is Founder-hero of Athens, known for slaying the Minotaur. Symbols: Sword, Sandals
Cadmus is Founder of Thebes, known for slaying a dragon and sowing its teeth. Symbols: Dragon teeth, Sword
Antigone is Daughter of Oedipus, known for her defiance of King Creon in burying her brother. Symbols: Funeral rites, Veil
Oedipus is King of Thebes who solved the riddle of the Sphinx and unwittingly fulfilled a prophecy. Symbols: Sphinx, Blindfold
Hector is Trojan prince and greatest warrior of Troy during the Trojan War. Symbols: Helmet, Sword
Hippolyta is Queen of the Amazons, known for her encounter with Heracles. Symbols: Girdle, Spear
Philoctetes is Greek hero, known for his archery skills and participation in the Trojan War. Symbols: Bow, Arrows
Hylas is Companion of Heracles, abducted by nymphs during the Argonauts' expedition. Symbols: Water jug, Club
Antiope is Amazonian queen and warrior, known for her marriage to Theseus. Symbols: Spear, Shield
Nestor is King of Pylos and a wise counselor in the Trojan War. Symbols: Scepter, Cup
Pandora is First woman in Greek mythology, known for opening a box that released all the evils of humanity. Symbols: Box, Curiosity
Tithonus is Trojan prince, lover of Eos (the dawn), granted immortality but not eternal youth. Symbols: Lyre, Cicada
Amphiaraus is A seer and hero of the Seven Against Thebes. Symbols: Serpent, Shield
Iphigenia is Daughter of Agamemnon, known for her sacrifice at Aulis. Symbols: Altar, Deer
Medea is Sorceress, wife of Jason, known for her revenge against him. Symbols: Cauldron, Dagger
Adonis is A youth of remarkable beauty, loved by Aphrodite. Symbols: Anemone, Boar
Peleus is Hero, father of Achilles, husband of the sea nymph Thetis. Symbols: Sword, Spear
Teucer is Archer and half-brother of Ajax the Great, fought in the Trojan War. Symbols: Bow, Arrow
Diomedes is Greek hero of the Trojan War, known for wounding Ares and Aphrodite. Symbols: Chariot, Spear
Andromache is Wife of Hector, embodiment of wifely devotion in Greek mythology. Symbols: Veil, City walls
Orion is Giant huntsman placed among the stars by Zeus. Symbols: Belt, Club
Aeneas is Trojan hero, ancestor of the Romans, son of Venus and Anchises. Symbols: Trojan Penates, Golden Bough
Daedalus is Legendary craftsman and artist, creator of the Labyrinth. Symbols: Labyrinth, Wings
Atlanta is Virgin huntress, only woman among the Argonauts. Symbols: Golden apples, Bow
Iphicles is Twin brother of Heracles, known for his mortality in contrast to his divine sibling. Symbols: Sword, Shield
Cassandra is Trojan princess with the gift of prophecy but cursed to never be believed. Symbols: Serpents, Laurel wreath
Odysseus is King of Ithaca, known for his cunning and ten-year journey home after the Trojan War. Symbols: Bow, Trojan Horse
Deucalion is Son of Prometheus, survivor of the great flood in Greek mythology. Symbols: Ark, Stones
Penthesilea is Amazonian queen who fought in the Trojan War. Symbols: Double-headed axe, Shield
Laocoon is Trojan priest who warned against the Trojan Horse. Symbols: Serpents, Spear
Icarus is Son of Daedalus who flew too close to the sun with wax wings. Symbols: Wax wings, Sun
Bellerophon is Hero who tamed Pegasus and slew the Chimera. Symbols: Pegasus, Spear
Alcestis is Queen of Pherae who sacrificed her life for her husband Admetus. Symbols: Veil, Sacrifice altar
Chrysippus is Prince of Elis, known for his beauty and tragic fate. Symbols: Chariot, Lyre
Electra is Daughter of Agamemnon, known for her role in avenging her father's death. Symbols: Urn, Dagger
Aenon is River god and lover of Aphrodite. Symbols: River, Reeds
Philemon is Pious old man who, with his wife Baucis, showed hospitality to disguised gods. Symbols: Oak tree, Temple
Nausicaa is Phaeacian princess who aided Odysseus. Symbols: Ball, Olive tree
Typhon is Monstrous offspring of Gaia and Tartarus. Father of many famous monsters. Symbols: Serpentine body, Fire-breathing
Cerberus is Guardian of the underworld, a three-headed hound. Symbols: Three heads, Snake tail
Medusa is One of the Gorgons, with snakes for hair and the ability to turn people to stone with her gaze. Symbols: Snake hair, Gorgon mask
Chimera is Fire-breathing hybrid creature with the body of a lion, the head of a goat arising from its back, and a tail that ended in a snake's head. Symbols: Lion body, Goat head, Snake tail
Scylla is A sea monster with twelve dog-heads and six snake-like lower bodies, who lived on one side of a narrow channel opposite her counterpart Charybdis. Symbols: Dog heads, Snake tails
Cyclops is Giant creatures with a single eye in the middle of their forehead, known for their forging abilities and association with the god Hephaestus. Symbols: Single eye, Massive size
Minotaur is Half-man, half-bull creature imprisoned in the Labyrinth of Crete, offspring of PasiphaÃ« and the Cretan Bull. Symbols: Bull head, Human body
Gorgons is Three monstrous sisters with snakes for hair, whose gaze turned people to stone. Stheno and Euryale were immortal, while Medusa was mortal. Symbols: Snake hair, Gorgon mask
Hydra is Lernaean serpent with multiple heads, capable of regeneration. One of Heracles' Twelve Labors was to slay it. Symbols: Many heads, Regenerative ability

Sirens is Dangerous creatures, portrayed as femmes fatales who lured nearby sailors with their enchanting music and voices to shipwreck on the rocky coast of their island. Symbols: Beautiful women, Bird feathers
Geryon is Three-bodied giant, master of a fabulous herd of red cattle of Geryon in the far west of the Mediterranean. Symbols: Three bodies, Herdsman's staff
Harpy is Half-woman, half-bird creatures known for stealing food and punishing the guilty. Symbols: Bird wings, Talons
Manticore is Legendary creature with the body of a lion, the face of a human, and the tail of a scorpion. Symbols: Lion body, Human face, Scorpion tail
Pegasus is Winged horse born from Medusa's blood when Perseus killed her. Symbols: Wings, Divine speed
Sphinx is Winged lion with the head of a human, known for her riddles and guarding the city of Thebes. Symbols: Lion body, Human head
Nemean Lion is Giant lion with impenetrable golden fur, slain by Heracles as his first labor. Symbols: Golden fur, Immunity to weapons
Orthrus is Two-headed dog and brother of Cerberus, owned by Geryon. Symbols: Two heads
Ladon is Hundred-headed dragon that guarded the golden apples of immortality in the Garden of the Hesperides. Symbols: Hundred heads, Serpentine body
Gigantes is Race of giant beings born from the blood of Uranus after his castration. Symbols: Massive size, Titanic strength
Centaur is Half-human, half-horse creatures known for their wild and unruly behavior. Symbols: Human torso, Horse body
Stymphalian Birds is Man-eating birds with bronze beaks, sharp metallic feathers, and toxic dung. Symbols: Bronze beaks, Metallic feathers
Empusa is Shape-shifting female monster with a bronze leg and a donkey's foot, known for seducing and devouring travelers. Symbols: Bronze leg, Donkey's foot
Erymanthian Boar is Enormous wild boar that terrorized the region around Mount Erymanthos. Symbols: Giant tusks, Immense size
Lamia is Child-eating daemon, once a beautiful queen of Libya cursed by Hera. Symbols: Serpentine lower body, Ability to remove eyes
Talos is Giant bronze automaton that protected Europa in Crete from pirates and invaders. Symbols: Bronze body, Single vein
Graeae is Three gray-haired sisters who shared one eye and one tooth among them. Symbols: Shared eye, Shared tooth
Aethon is Giant eagle sent by Zeus to eat Prometheus' liver as punishment. Symbols: Giant wings, Sharp beak
Cetus is Enormous sea monster sent by Poseidon to ravage the kingdom of Ethiopia. Symbols: Serpentine body, Massive jaws
Mormo is Fearsome female spirit who bit bad children and was used to frighten them into obedience. Symbols: Sharp teeth, Changing form
Phaea is The Crommyonian Sow, a wild pig that ravaged the area around Crommyon. Symbols: Enormous size, Destructive nature
Skolopendra is Gigantic sea monster resembling a centipede, with multiple legs and a voracious appetite. Symbols: Numerous legs, Elongated body
Leucrocotta is Hybrid beast with the body of a lion, the head of a badger, and cloven hooves. Symbols: Lion body, Badger head, Cloven hooves
Pyrausta is Small, four-legged winged creature that lived in fire and died if it flew too far from it. Symbols: Wings, Fiery habitat
Karkinos is Giant crab that fought alongside the Hydra against Heracles. Symbols: Giant pincers, Hard shell
Ophiotaurus is Creature with the front of a bull and the rear of a serpent, whose entrails granted the power to defeat the gods. Symbols: Bull head, Serpent tail
Taraxippus is Ghost or spirit that frightened horses at hippodromes, causing them to panic during races. Symbols: Invisible presence, Horse panic
Teumessian Fox is Gigantic fox destined never to be caught, sent by the gods to punish the city of Thebes. Symbols: Uncatchable speed, Fox form
Aspidochelone is A massive sea creature resembling an island, luring sailors to their doom. Symbols: Island-like back, Deceptive stillness
Ichthyocentaurs is Sea-dwelling creatures with the upper body of a human, the lower front of a horse, and the tail of a fish. Symbols: Fish tail, Horse legs, Human torso
Campe is Draconic monster with a woman's head and torso, the lower body of a dragon, and various animal heads around her waist. Symbols: Multiple animal heads, Dragon body
Hippalectryon is Hybrid creature with the front half of a horse and the rear of a rooster. Symbols: Horse head, Rooster tail
Odontotyrannos is Massive beast with elephant-like tusks and a voracious appetite for human flesh. Symbols: Enormous tusks, Man-eating maw
Crocotta is A mythical dog-wolf of India, said to imitate human voices to lure prey. Symbols: Mane of a lion, Jaws of incredible strength
Cercopes is Mischievous forest creatures known for their thieving and deceitful nature. Symbols: Monkey-like appearance, Trickster grins
Cecrops is Mythical first king of Athens, half-man and half-snake. Symbols: Snake lower body, Human upper body
Scolopendra is Giant sea serpent with numerous legs, capable of beaching ships. Symbols: Multitude of legs, Serpentine body
Striges is Nocturnal bird-like creatures that fed on human flesh and blood. Symbols: Owl-like appearance, Sharp talons
Telekhines is Sea demons with flippers for hands and dog-like heads, skilled in metallurgy. Symbols: Dog heads, Flipper hands
Hecatonchires is Giants with a hundred hands and fifty heads, brothers of the Cyclopes. Symbols: Hundred hands, Fifty heads
Arae is Female spirits of curses, particularly of the curses placed by the dead upon those guilty of their death. Symbols: Dark wings, Bloody talons
Hippocamp is Mythical creature with the upper body of a horse and the lower body of a fish. Symbols: Horse head, Fish tail
Cerastes is Aggressive horned serpents known for their deadly ambush tactics. Symbols: Horns, Snake body
Amphisbaena is Serpent with a head at each end, allowing it to move in either direction. Symbols: Two heads, Serpentine body
Catoblepas is A buffalo-like creature with a head so heavy it could only look downwards, turning any creature that met its gaze to stone. Symbols: Heavy head, Deadly gaze
Empousai is Female vampiric demons with flaming hair, one bronze leg and one donkey leg. Symbols: Flaming hair, Mismatched legs
Ophiotaurus is A creature with the front half of a bull and the rear half of a serpent. Symbols: Bull head, Serpent tail
Taraxippus is A malevolent spirit that spooked horses at racetracks, causing them to panic. Symbols: Invisible presence, Horse panic
Ceuthonymus is A monstrous being said to drag the souls of the dead down to the underworld. Symbols: Dark form, Soul-dragging chains
Pyrisoous is A giant, flaming boar that ravaged the countryside. Symbols: Flaming tusks, Bristling fire
Cychreides is A giant serpent that terrorized the island of Salamis before being driven out or slain. Symbols: Enormous size, Serpentine form
Cetus is A sea monster sent by Poseidon to ravage the kingdom of Aethiopia. Symbols: Whale-like body, Serpentine features
Lycanthrope is Humans with the ability to shapeshift into wolves or wolf-like creatures. Symbols: Wolf form, Full moon
Strix is Nocturnal bird of ill omen that fed on human flesh and blood. Symbols: Owl-like appearance, Hooked beak
Scylla is Sea monster with multiple heads and dog-like lower bodies. Symbols: Multiple heads, Dog-like lower bodies
Charybdis is Sea monster that created whirlpools by sucking in and spitting out vast amounts of water. Symbols: Whirlpool, Gaping maw
Nemean Lion is A monstrous lion with an impenetrable golden fur. Symbols: Golden fur, Invulnerability
Crommyonian Sow is A giant pig that ravaged the area around Crommyon. Symbols: Enormous size, Destructive nature
Teumessian Fox is A giant fox destined never to be caught, sent to ravage the countryside of Thebes. Symbols: Uncatchable speed, Fox form
Panes is Goat-legged nature spirits known for their mischievous behavior and musical abilities. Symbols: Goat legs, Pan flute
Talos is A giant bronze automaton that protected Europa in Crete. Symbols: Bronze body, Single vein of ichor
Gegenees is A race of six-armed giants that inhabited the island of Bear Mountain. Symbols: Six arms, Massive size
Keres is Female death-spirits who personified violent death and were drawn to battlefields. Symbols: Black wings, Bloody talons
Mormo is A fearsome female spirit used to frighten children into obedience. Symbols: Vampiric features, Terrifying visage
Alcyoneus is The eldest of the Giants, born to oppose the Olympian gods. Symbols: Massive size, Immortality on native soil
Antaeus is A giant who challenged passersby to wrestling matches and gained strength from contact with the earth. Symbols: Wrestling stance, Connection to earth
Argus Panoptes is A giant with a hundred eyes, known for his watchfulness. Symbols: Hundred eyes, Watchful gaze
Colchian Dragon is A sleepless dragon that guarded the Golden Fleece. Symbols: Coiled serpent, Vigilant eyes
Python is A monstrous serpent that lived in the center of the earth, guarding the Oracle of Delphi. Symbols: Coiled serpent, Oracle guardian
Steropes is One of the elder Cyclopes, known for creating Zeus's thunderbolts. Symbols: Single eye, Thunderbolt
